# 1980 United States presidential election in North Carolina  

The 1980 United States presidential election in North Carolina took place on November 4, 1980, as part of the broader [1980 United States presidential election](/1980_United_States_presidential_election). Voters chose 13 representatives, or electors to the [Electoral College](/United_States_Electoral_College), who voted for [president](/President_of_the_United_States) and [vice president](/Vice_President_of_the_United_States).  

North Carolina barely voted for the [Republican](/Republican_Party_(United_States)) nominee, [Governor](/Governor_of_California) [Ronald Reagan](/Ronald_Reagan), over the [Democratic](/Democratic_Party_(United_States)) nominee, [President](/President_of_the_United_States) [Jimmy Carter](/Jimmy_Carter) in a close battle. Independent [John B. Anderson](/John_B._Anderson), who won 2 % of the vote from Reagan and Carter in the state, nevertheless forced both major‑party candidates to contend with a third‑party presence. The final numbers were 49.30 % for Reagan to 47.18 % for Carter and 2.85 % for Anderson.  

As of the [2024 presidential election](/2024_United_States_presidential_election_in_North_Carolina), this remains the last election in which the following counties have voted for a Democratic presidential candidate: [Cleveland](/Cleveland_County,_North_Carolina), [Currituck](/Currituck_County,_North_Carolina), [Harnett](/Harnett_County,_North_Carolina), [Lee](/Lee_County,_North_Carolina), [Person](/Person_County,_North_Carolina) and [Union](/Union_County,_North_Carolina). &#91;2&#93;  

Among white voters, 57 % supported Reagan while 39 % supported Carter. &#91;3&#93; &#91;4&#93;  

